The paper discusses the third edition of Google Scholar Metrics, which is a bibliometric tool used to measure the impact of scientific publications. The paper focuses on the features, strengths, and weaknesses of this tool, and presents figures related to the number of publications, publication types, languages, and h5-index and h5-median values by language, subject area, and subcategory. Given this focus, the most likely sub-categories are those related to information retrieval (cs.IR), digital libraries (cs.DL), cybersecurity (cs.CR), complex systems (cs.CY), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
